  "response": "There are several important legal precedents related to money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Bajakajian (1998)\n- Supreme Court case addressing civil asset forfeiture\n- Established limits on government's ability to seize assets\n\n2. United States v. Santos (2008)\n- Defined \"proceeds\" in money laundering statutes\n- Clarified interpretation of financial transaction laws\n\n3. Bank Secrecy Act cases\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Defined compliance standards for detecting potential laundering\n\n4. RICO Act prosecutions\n- Used to combat organized crime financial activities\n- Provided broader framework for prosecuting money laundering\n\n5. International cases involving cross-border transactions\n- Set precedents for jurisdictional investigations\n- Established frameworks for international cooperation\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific precedents or discuss additional legal developments in money laundering law?",
